# EXTRACTOR_CONTRACT_VERSION: 1
#
# This marker MUST stay the file's first non-blank line (mirrors the
# `<!-- PROMPT_CONTRACT_VERSION: N -->` convention `translate_TASK.md` /
# `review_TASK.md` / `glossary_TASK.md` use, generalized to a Python `#`
# comment since this file must stay valid Python). On a resumed project,
# `scripts/profile_validate.py` compares this value against its own hardcoded
# `CURRENT_EXTRACTOR_CONTRACT_VERSION` constant and FATALLY halts on: a
# missing marker, a malformed (non-integer) value, a duplicated marker, or a
# non-leading marker. Bump both this line and that constant together whenever
# this file's I/O contract (manifest.json shape, block-ID model, sentinel
# conventions) changes in a way old projects must consciously re-adopt --
# NEVER auto-overwrite a project's already-hand-adapted `extract.py`.
"""Deterministic extractor -- gutenberg_epub adapter (config-driven).

Generalized from the proven, production-run extractor built for Historiettes
de Tallemant, tome 3 (fr->ru). Keeps that script's core mechanics -- the
block-ID/order_index coverage model, spine + front/back classification,
footnote grouping, verse detection, and the blocking round-trip self-check
suite -- but drives every per-project decision off `profile.yml` instead of
hardcoded constants, and self-anchors under `${durable_root}` instead of an
absolute path baked in at authoring time.

This file IS the `gutenberg_epub` adapter's extractor (see
`references/source-format-adapters/gutenberg-epub.md`). It refuses to run
against a profile whose `source.format` is anything else -- `plain_text`
sources use a separate, lighter adapter (segmentation-heuristic based, no
EPUB spine/OPF concept at all); `custom` sources use a hand-co-designed
extractor under `scripts/custom_extractors/`. A v1.1 dispatcher that shares
this file across formats is plausible future work, not this build's scope.

Shipped location: Step 0a copies this template, ONCE, to
`${durable_root}/extract.py` (a one-time seed, never re-copied over a
project's own hand-adapted copy) -- a SIBLING of `scripts/`, `segments/`,
`manifest.json`, etc., NOT a member of `scripts/` itself. That is why this
file self-anchors via `Path(__file__).resolve().parent` (one level up from
where a generic `${durable_root}/scripts/<name>.py` script would use
`.parents[1]`) -- getting this wrong silently resolves `durable_root` one
directory too high and corrupts every path derived from it.

Block-ID model
---------------
  HEAD:{seg}            chapter/novella heading (source h2)
  PARA:{seg}:{ord}      prose paragraph
  QUOTE:{seg}:{ord}     block quotation (blockquote-equivalent, wrapper kept)
  VERSE:{seg}:{ord}     standalone poem node (top-level poetry node in a segment)
  FN:{N}                footnote definition N (only when footnotes.apparatus_policy
                        is translate_all/preserve_source -- see build_footnote_table)
  FRONTBACK:{id}        front/back element, decision translate|regenerate|omit

Sentinels
---------
  U+27E6 FNREF_N U+27E7          marks the exact in-sentence position of footnote
                                 anchor N (translate_all/preserve_source only).
  U+27E6 VERSE_Vddd_hash U+27E7  marks an embedded poem (inside a quote/footnote/
                                 frontback block); the poem is translated via the
                                 verse sub-pipeline and substituted back at assembly.
  [N]                            literal footnote marker baked into plain text
                                 verbatim when footnotes.apparatus_policy is
                                 body_refs_only -- no apparatus exists to point at,
                                 the reader just sees "there was a note here".

Standalone body poems are their own VERSE block. Poems nested in a quote,
footnote, or frontback block are replaced in place by a VERSE placeholder and
recorded in the verse store with mount="embedded" plus the parent block that
carries the placeholder.
"""
